<p>The explanation of the capacitor max voltage was very helpful.  Something I never knew about.</p>
</div><div class="comments"><div class="comment-arrow"><img src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_commentarrow_top.gif"></div><div class="comment" id="comment_1130"><img class="avatar" src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/1ff6ad39b8c242a14296a76845e116cd?d=retro&s=30&r=pg" width=30 height=30 /><span class="header"><img class="employee" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/comment_is_internal.gif" title="SparkFun Employee" alt="SparkFun Employee" /> <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/7185" class="bold">Nate</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>December  3, 2008 at  9:29 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_1130">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Good points. I've added more on the PTC and caps. Larger caps obviously store more energy, but they react more slowly. If you have a large power outage (power dips for 10-100ms), a big cap (100uF to 1000uF) will help 'hold up' the falling voltage. A smaller cap (0.1uF) will help suppress higher frequency noise and shorter power dips (noise in the 1us to 100us range). Therefore, 0.1uF caps are located near the microcontroller to help with short bursts, where 100uF and 10uF caps are used on the power rails.</p>
</div></div></div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_1419"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/52971" class="bold">peterb</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January  6, 2009 at  3:55 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_1419">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>this is a great tutorial, having fun.
